Hunter's Creek along Sandbeach Lake Trail - Hiking Trail Crossed Over Hunter's Creek where I sat with my feet dangling over the crossing, watching the ripples and fish.  Signage along the trail and at Sandbeach Lake indicate Greenback Cutthroat Trout.

5 Species of Trout in the Park - 3 Non Natives (Brook, Brown, Rainbow) introduced in the Park and can still be found at specific locations, but not this location.

2 Native Species - Greenback and Colorado Cutthroat   - The lake and creek are east of the continental divide, indicating they should be greenback, although a few fascinating reads indicate that historical mistakes were made and some fish introduced on the eastern side were Colorado Cutthroat genetics.

All the evidence, I have found indicate that this watershed was targeted for Greenback restoration, including removal of non greenback species.

Fascinating stuff.

Side Note - according to
https://www.fishexplorer.com/co/lakedet.asp?lid=3720
there are NO other species there, but obviously I have no way to know that is 100% correct.

Caught this incredible Lake Trout from shore using a 1/2 oz silver Kastmaster with 10lb fluorocarbon line, and a 6 foot medium-action rod. I cast as far as I could from shore, waited for the lure to hit the bottom, and popped it off the bottom with two quick lifts. After popping it, I would wait a few seconds for the lure to descend before popping it again. On one of the descents, this laker took the lure and went on a crazy run that almost spooled my reel. I fought it hard for 10-20 minutes and my dad helped me land it. After snapping a couple photos, we revived the fish and sent it back to its deep water haunts. What an incredible experience! There are only two times of year when it is likely to catch a laker from shore here: in mid-late May at ice-off when they come shallow to feed and in November right before the lake freezes when they are spawning on rock shelves along steep banks.

My dad caught this awesome Lake Trout from shore using a whole dead 4 inch minnow with a 2/0 circle hook and 2 oz of egg sinkers. He winged the bait out as far as he could, tightened up the slack a bit, and opened the bail waiting for a laker to run with bait. After 20 minutes or so, this fish took the bait, he let it run for half a minute, and then set the hook. The fish put up a strong fight with several runs. After snapping a couple pics, we returned this amazing creature back into the water.
